  "intent": "Define the SecurityRecipes agent handoff boundary for MCP, A2A, provider-native subagents, and human approval bridges so multi-agent workflows can exchange only approved context metadata, cited evidence, and explicit approval state while preserving least privilege and auditability.",
  "positioning": {
    "buyer": "AI Platform, Security Engineering, AppSec, GRC, procurement security, vendor-risk, model-risk, and acquisition diligence teams",
    "category": "Agent-to-agent handoff boundary and protocol trust evidence",
    "enterprise_promise": "SecurityRecipes can decide whether a proposed agent handoff is metadata-only, cited-evidence, approval-gated, denied, or session-ending before context crosses an agent, protocol, tenant, or organization boundary.",
    "why_now": "Enterprises are standardizing on MCP for agent-to-tool access and A2A for agent-to-agent coordination. The scarce control surface is no longer only which tool an agent can call; it is whether delegated agents receive the minimum context, authority, identity, and evidence needed for a task."
  },
